  <marc:subfield code="a">This is a fragment of a H&#x323;umash, or Hebrew Bible, styled to accommodate the Talmudic custom (statement of Rav Ammi, recorded in Babylonian Talmud Berakhot 8a) of Shenayim mik&#x323;ra v&#x323;e-&#x2BC;eh&#x323;ad Targum (to recite the text twice with the Targum once). The surviving text begins with Targum to Leviticus 23:10 with the words &#x5D5;&#x5B0;&#x5EA;&#x5B7;&#x5D9;&#x5B0;&#x5EA;&#x5D5;&#x5BC;&#x5DF; &#x5D9;&#x5B8;&#x5EA; &#x5E2;&#x5D5;&#x5BC;&#x5DE;&#x5B0;&#x5E8;&#x5B8;&#x5D0; &#x5E8;&#x5B5;&#x5D9;&#x5E9;&#x5C1; &#x5D7;&#x5B2;&#x5E6;&#x5B8;&#x5D3;&#x5B0;&#x5DB;&#x5D5;&#x5B9;&#x5DF; &#x5DC;&#x5B0;&#x5D5;&#x5B8;&#x5EA; &#x5DB;&#x5BC;&#x5B7;&#x5D4;&#x5B2;&#x5E0;&#x5B8;&#x5D0;, the text of Leviticus 23:11, and the first word of the Targum on that verse (&#x5D5;&#x5B4;&#x5D9;&#x5E8;&#x5B4;&#x5D9;&#x5DD;). The verso of this fragment has absorbed text from Halper 12, a leaf of a Spanish mik&#x323;ra codex with the same text dating about a century earlier. This was possibly a student's copy created perhaps in Egypt between 1300 and 1499.</marc:subfield>
